Package nl.naturalis.common.collection

Class TypeHashMap<V>

java.lang.Object
nl.naturalis.common.x.collection.ImmutableMap<Class<?>,V>
nl.naturalis.common.collection.TypeHashMap<V>
Type Parameters:
V - The type of the values in the Map
All Implemented Interfaces:
Map<Class<?>,V>, TypeMap<V>
public final class TypeHashMap<V> extends ImmutableMap<Class<?>,V>
A TypeMap that is internally backed by a regular Map. Type lookups may involve several queries against the backing map. If a type, requested via get or containsKey, is not itself present in the backing map, the TypeHashMap will first climb up the type's class hierarchy and then up its interface hierarchy to see if any of its supertypes is.

Auto-expansion

As required by the TypeMap specification, TypeHashMap is an immutable class. All map-altering methods throw an UnsupportedOperationException. However, it can be configured to tacitly absorb new types upon being requested, provided the new type is a subtype of a type that is already in the map. The new type will then be associated with the same value as the supertype. Thus, when the type is requested again, it will result in a direct hit. In the end, a TypeHashMap will be nothing but a pass-through shell around the HashMap that backs it - and perform as such.

(Implementation node: with auto-expansion disabled, the backing map is not actually a HashMap.)

Author:
Ayco Holleman
